# RFC 9115 {#rfcnum}

# An Automatic Certificate Management Environment (ACME) Profile for Generating Delegated Certificates {#title}

::: {#section-abstract .section}
## [Abstract](#abstract){.selfRef}

This document defines a profile of the Automatic Certificate Management
Environment (ACME) protocol by which the holder of an identifier (e.g.,
a domain name) can allow a third party to obtain an X.509 certificate
such that the certificate subject is the delegated identifier while the
certified public key corresponds to a private key controlled by the
third party. A primary use case is that of a Content Delivery Network
(CDN), the third party, terminating TLS sessions on behalf of a content
provider (the holder of a domain name). The presented mechanism allows
the holder of the identifier to retain control over the delegation and
revoke it at any time. Importantly, this mechanism does not require any
modification to the deployed TLS clients and
servers.[¶](#section-abstract-1){.pilcrow}
:::

::: {#introduction}
::: {#section-1 .section}
## [1.](#section-1){.section-number .selfRef} [Introduction](#name-introduction){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-introduction}

This document is related to \[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\], in that some
important use cases require both documents to be implemented. To avoid
duplication, we give here a bare-bones description of the motivation for
this solution. For more details, please refer to the introductory
sections of \[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\].[¶](#section-1-1){.pilcrow}

An Identifier Owner (IdO) has agreements in place with one or more Name
Delegation Consumer (NDC) to use and attest its
identity.[¶](#section-1-2){.pilcrow}

In the primary use case, the IdO is a content provider, and we consider
a Content Delivery Network (CDN) provider contracted to serve the
content over HTTPS. The CDN terminates the HTTPS connection at one of
its edge cache servers and needs to present its clients (browsers,
mobile apps, set-top boxes) a certificate whose name matches the domain
name of the URL that is requested, i.e., that of the IdO.
Understandably, some IdOs may balk at sharing their long-term private
keys with another organization; equally, delegates would rather not have
to handle other parties\' long-term secrets. Other relevant use cases
are discussed in [Section
5](#further-use-cases){.xref}.[¶](#section-1-3){.pilcrow}

This document describes a profile of the ACME protocol
\[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\] that allows the NDC to request from the
IdO, acting as a profiled ACME server, a certificate for a delegated
identity \-- i.e., one belonging to the IdO. The IdO then uses the ACME
protocol (with the extensions described in
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\]) to request issuance of a Short-Term,
Automatically Renewed (STAR) certificate for the same delegated
identity. The generated short-term certificate is automatically renewed
by the ACME Certification Authority (CA), is periodically fetched by the
NDC, and is used to terminate HTTPS connections in lieu of the IdO. The
IdO can end the delegation at any time by simply instructing the CA to
stop the automatic renewal and letting the certificate expire shortly
thereafter.[¶](#section-1-4){.pilcrow}

While the primary use case we address is a delegation of STAR
certificates, the mechanism proposed here also accommodates long-lived
certificates managed with the ACME protocol. The most noticeable
difference between long-lived and STAR certificates is the way the
termination of the delegation is managed. In the case of long-lived
certificates, the IdO uses the `revokeCert` URL exposed by the CA and
waits for the explicit revocation based on the Certificate Revocation
List (CRL) and Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) to propagate to
the relying parties.[¶](#section-1-5){.pilcrow}

In case the delegated identity is a domain name, this document also
provides a way for the NDC to inform the IdO about the CNAME mappings
that need to be installed in the IdO\'s DNS zone to enable the aliasing
of the delegated name, thus allowing the complete name delegation
workflow to be handled using a single
interface.[¶](#section-1-6){.pilcrow}

We note that other standardization efforts address the problem of
certificate delegation for TLS connections, specifically
\[[TLS-SUBCERTS](#I-D.ietf-tls-subcerts){.xref}\] and
\[[MGLT-LURK-TLS13](#I-D.mglt-lurk-tls13){.xref}\]. The former extends
the TLS certificate chain with a customer-owned signing certificate; the
latter separates the server\'s private key into a dedicated, more-secure
component. Compared to these other approaches, the current document does
not require changes to the TLS network stack of the client or the
server, nor does it introduce additional latency to the TLS
connection.[¶](#section-1-7){.pilcrow}

::: {#terminology}
::: {#section-1.1 .section}
### [1.1.](#section-1.1){.section-number .selfRef} [Terminology](#name-terminology){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-terminology}

[]{.break}

IdO

:   Identifier Owner, the holder (current owner) of an identifier (e.g.,
    a domain name) that needs to be delegated. Depending on the context,
    the term IdO may also be used to designate the (profiled) ACME
    server deployed by the Identifier Owner or the ACME client used by
    the Identifier Owner to interact with the
    CA.[¶](#section-1.1-1.2.1){.pilcrow}

:   

NDC

:   Name Delegation Consumer, the entity to which the domain name is
    delegated for a limited time. This is a CDN in the primary use case
    (in fact, readers may note the similarity of the two abbreviations).
    Depending on the context, the term NDC may also be used to designate
    the (profiled) ACME client used by the Name Delegation
    Consumer.[¶](#section-1.1-1.4.1){.pilcrow}

:   

CDN

:   Content Delivery Network, a widely distributed network that serves
    the domain\'s web content to a wide audience at high
    performance.[¶](#section-1.1-1.6.1){.pilcrow}

:   

STAR

:   Short-Term, Automatically Renewed, as applied to X.509
    certificates.[¶](#section-1.1-1.8.1){.pilcrow}

:   

ACME

:   Automated Certificate Management Environment, a certificate
    management protocol
    \[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\].[¶](#section-1.1-1.10.1){.pilcrow}

:   

CA

:   Certification Authority, specifically one that implements the ACME
    protocol. In this document, the term is synonymous with \"ACME
    server deployed by the Certification
    Authority\".[¶](#section-1.1-1.12.1){.pilcrow}

:   

CSR

:   Certificate Signing Request, specifically a PKCS#10
    \[[RFC2986](#RFC2986){.xref}\] Certificate Signing Request, as
    supported by ACME.[¶](#section-1.1-1.14.1){.pilcrow}

:   

FQDN

:   Fully Qualified Domain Name.[¶](#section-1.1-1.16.1){.pilcrow}

:

## [2.](#section-2){.section-number .selfRef} [Protocol Flow](#name-protocol-flow){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-protocol-flow}

This section presents the protocol flow. For completeness, we include
the ACME profile proposed in this document as well as the ACME STAR
protocol described in
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\].[¶](#section-2-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#proto-preconditions}
::: {#section-2.1 .section}
### [2.1.](#section-2.1){.section-number .selfRef} [Preconditions](#name-preconditions){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-preconditions}

The protocol assumes the following preconditions are
met:[¶](#section-2.1-1){.pilcrow}

-   [The IdO exposes an ACME server interface to the NDC(s) comprising
    the account management
    interface.[¶](#section-2.1-2.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.1-2.1}
-   [The NDC has registered an ACME account with the
    IdO.[¶](#section-2.1-2.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.1-2.2}
-   [The NDC and IdO have agreed on a \"CSR template\" to use, including
    at a minimum: subject name (e.g., `abc.ido.example`), requested
    algorithms and key length, key usage, and extensions. The NDC will
    use this template for every CSR created under the same
    delegation.[¶](#section-2.1-2.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.1-2.3}
-   [The IdO has registered an ACME account with the Certification
    Authority (CA).[¶](#section-2.1-2.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.1-2.4}

Note that even if the IdO implements the ACME server role, it is not
acting as a CA; in fact, from the point of view of the certificate
issuance process, the IdO only works as a \"policing\" forwarder of the
NDC\'s key pair and is responsible for completing the identity
verification process towards the CA.[¶](#section-2.1-3){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#overview}
::: {#section-2.2 .section}
### [2.2.](#section-2.2){.section-number .selfRef} [Overview](#name-overview){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-overview}

For clarity, the protocol overview presented here covers the main use
case of this protocol, namely delegation of STAR certificates. Protocol
behavior for non-STAR certificates is similar, and the detailed
differences are listed in the following
sections.[¶](#section-2.2-1){.pilcrow}

The interaction between the NDC and the IdO is governed by the profiled
ACME workflow detailed in [Section 2.3](#sec-profile){.xref}. The
interaction between the IdO and the CA is ruled by ACME
\[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\], ACME STAR
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\], and any other ACME extension that
applies (e.g.,
\[[TOKEN-TNAUTHLIST](#I-D.ietf-acme-authority-token-tnauthlist){.xref}\]
for Secure Telephone Identity Revisited
(STIR)).[¶](#section-2.2-2){.pilcrow}

The outline of the combined protocol for STAR certificates is as follows
([Figure 1](#fig-endtoend){.xref}):[¶](#section-2.2-3){.pilcrow}

-   [NDC sends an Order1 for the delegated identifier to
    IdO.[¶](#section-2.2-4.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.2-4.1}
-   [IdO creates an Order1 resource in state `ready` with a `finalize`
    URL.[¶](#section-2.2-4.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.2-4.2}
-   [NDC immediately sends a `finalize` request (which includes the CSR)
    to the IdO.[¶](#section-2.2-4.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.2-4.3}
-   [IdO verifies the CSR according to the agreed upon CSR
    template.[¶](#section-2.2-4.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.2-4.4}
-   [If the CSR verification fails, Order1 is moved to an `invalid`
    state and everything
    stops.[¶](#section-2.2-4.5){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.2-4.5}
-   [If the CSR verification is successful, IdO moves Order1 to state
    `processing` and sends a new Order2 (using its own account) for the
    delegated identifier to the
    CA.[¶](#section-2.2-4.6){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.2-4.6}
-   [If the ACME STAR protocol fails, Order2 moves to `invalid`, and the
    same state is reflected in Order1 (i.e., the NDC
    Order).[¶](#section-2.2-4.7){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.2-4.7}
-   [If the ACME STAR run is successful (i.e., Order2 is `valid`), IdO
    copies the `star-certificate` URL from Order2 to Order1 and updates
    the Order1 state to
    `valid`.[¶](#section-2.2-4.8){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.2-4.8}

The NDC can now download, install, and use the short-term certificate
bearing the name delegated by the IdO. The STAR certificate can be used
until it expires, at which time the NDC is guaranteed to find a new
certificate it can download, install, and use. This continues with
subsequent certificates until either Order1 expires or the IdO decides
to cancel the automatic renewal process with the
CA.[¶](#section-2.2-5){.pilcrow}

Note that the interactive identifier authorization phase described in
[Section
7.5](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8555#section-7.5){.relref} of
\[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\] is suppressed on the NDC-IdO side because
the delegated identity contained in the CSR presented to the IdO is
validated against the configured CSR template ([Section
4.1](#sec-csr-template-syntax){.xref}). Therefore, the NDC sends the
`finalize` request, including the CSR, to the IdO immediately after
Order1 has been acknowledged. The IdO [SHALL]{.bcp14} buffer a (valid)
CSR until the Validation phase completes
successfully.[¶](#section-2.2-6){.pilcrow}

Also note that the successful negotiation of the unauthenticated GET
([Section
3.4](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8739#section-3.4){.relref} of
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\]) is required in order to allow the NDC to
access the `star-certificate` URL on the
CA.[¶](#section-2.2-7){.pilcrow}

Flow](#name-end-to-end-star-delegation-){.selfRef}

::: {#sec-profile}
::: {#section-2.3 .section}
### [2.3.](#section-2.3){.section-number .selfRef} [Delegated Identity Profile](#name-delegated-identity-profile){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-delegated-identity-profile}

This section defines a profile of the ACME protocol to be used between
the NDC and IdO.[¶](#section-2.3-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#sec-profile-dele-config}
::: {#section-2.3.1 .section}
#### [2.3.1.](#section-2.3.1){.section-number .selfRef} [Delegation Configuration](#name-delegation-configuration){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-delegation-configuration}

The IdO must be preconfigured to recognize one or more NDCs and present
them with details about certificate delegations that apply to each
one.[¶](#section-2.3.1-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#account-object-extensions}
::: {#section-2.3.1.1 .section}
##### [2.3.1.1.](#section-2.3.1.1){.section-number .selfRef} [Account Object Extensions](#name-account-object-extensions){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-account-object-extensions}

An NDC identifies itself to the IdO as an ACME account. The IdO can
delegate multiple names to an NDC, and these configurations are
described through `delegation` objects associated with the NDC\'s
account object on the IdO.[¶](#section-2.3.1.1-1){.pilcrow}

As shown in [Figure 2](#fig-account-object){.xref}, the ACME account
resource on the IdO is extended with a new `delegations`
attribute:[¶](#section-2.3.1.1-2){.pilcrow}

[]{.break}

delegations (required, string):
:   A URL from which a list of delegations configured for this account
    ([Section 2.3.1.3](#sec-delegation-objects){.xref}) can be fetched
    via a POST-as-GET request.[¶](#section-2.3.1.1-3.2){.pilcrow}
:   

[]{#name-example-account-object-with}

::: {#fig-account-object}
::: {#section-2.3.1.1-4.1 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft}
    {
      "status": "valid",
      "contact": [
        "mailto:delegation-admin@ido.example"
      ],
      "termsOfServiceAgreed": true,
      "orders": "https://example.com/acme/orders/saHpfB",
      "delegations": "https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegations/adFqoz"
    }
:::

[Figure 2](#figure-2){.selfRef}: [Example Account Object with
Delegations](#name-example-account-object-with){.selfRef}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#delegation-lists}
::: {#section-2.3.1.2 .section}
##### [2.3.1.2.](#section-2.3.1.2){.section-number .selfRef} [Delegation Lists](#name-delegation-lists){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-delegation-lists}

Each account object includes a `delegations` URL from which a list of
delegation configurations created by the IdO can be fetched via a
POST-as-GET request. The result of the request [MUST]{.bcp14} be a JSON
object whose `delegations` field is an array of URLs, each identifying a
delegation configuration made available to the NDC account ([Section
2.3.1.3](#sec-delegation-objects){.xref}). The server [MAY]{.bcp14}
return an incomplete list, along with a `Link` header field with a
`next` link relation indicating where further entries can be
acquired.[¶](#section-2.3.1.2-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-2.3.1.2-2}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-json}
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: application/json
Link: <https://acme.ido.example/acme/directory>;rel="index"
Link: <https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegations/adFqoz?/
      cursor=2>;rel="next"

{
  "delegations": [
    "https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegation/ogfr8EcolOT",
    "https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegation/wSi5Lbb61E4",
    /* more URLs not shown for example brevity */
    "https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegation/gm0wfLYHBen"
  ]
}
```

[¶](#section-2.3.1.2-2){.pilcrow}
:::

Note that in the figure above,
https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegations/adFqoz?cursor=2 includes a
line break for the sake of
presentation.[¶](#section-2.3.1.2-3){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#sec-delegation-objects}
::: {#section-2.3.1.3 .section}
##### [2.3.1.3.](#section-2.3.1.3){.section-number .selfRef} [Delegation Objects](#name-delegation-objects){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-delegation-objects}

This profile extends the ACME resource model with a new read-only
`delegation` object that represents a delegation configuration that
applies to a given NDC.[¶](#section-2.3.1.3-1){.pilcrow}

A `delegation` object contains the CSR template (see [Section
4](#sec-csr-template){.xref}) that applies to that delegation and,
optionally, any related CNAME mapping for the delegated identifiers. Its
structure is as follows:[¶](#section-2.3.1.3-2){.pilcrow}

[]{.break}

csr-template (required, object):
:   CSR template, as defined in [Section
    4](#sec-csr-template){.xref}.[¶](#section-2.3.1.3-3.2){.pilcrow}
:   

cname-map (optional, object):
:   A map of FQDN pairs. In each pair, the name is the delegated
    identifier; the value is the corresponding NDC name that is aliased
    in the IdO\'s zone file to redirect the resolvers to the delegated
    entity. Both names and values [MUST]{.bcp14} be FQDNs with a
    terminating \'.\'. This field is only meaningful for identifiers of
    type `dns`.[¶](#section-2.3.1.3-3.4){.pilcrow}
:   

An example `delegation` object in JSON format is shown in [Figure
3](#fig-configuration-object){.xref}.[¶](#section-2.3.1.3-4){.pilcrow}

[]{#name-example-delegation-configur}

::: {#fig-configuration-object}
::: {#section-2.3.1.3-5.1}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-json}
{
  "csr-template": {
    "keyTypes": [
      {
        "PublicKeyType": "id-ecPublicKey",
        "namedCurve": "secp256r1",
        "SignatureType": "ecdsa-with-SHA256"
      }
    ],
    "subject": {
      "country": "CA",
      "stateOrProvince": "**",
      "locality": "**"
    },
    "extensions": {
      "subjectAltName": {
        "DNS": [
          "abc.ido.example"
        ]
      },
      "keyUsage": [
        "digitalSignature"
      ],
      "extendedKeyUsage": [
        "serverAuth"
      ]
    }
  },
  "cname-map": {
    "abc.ido.example.": "abc.ndc.example."
  }
}
```
:::

[Figure 3](#figure-3){.selfRef}: [Example Delegation Configuration
Object](#name-example-delegation-configur){.selfRef}
:::

In order to indicate which specific delegation applies to the requested
certificate, a new `delegation` attribute is added to the order object
on the NDC-IdO side (see Figures [4](#fig-star-ndc-neworder){.xref} and
[7](#fig-non-star-ndc-neworder){.xref}). The value of this attribute is
the URL pointing to the delegation configuration object that is to be
used for this certificate request. If the `delegation` attribute in the
order object contains a URL that does not correspond to a configuration
available to the requesting ACME account, the IdO [MUST]{.bcp14} return
an error response with status code 403 (Forbidden), providing a problem
document \[[RFC7807](#RFC7807){.xref}\] with type
`urn:ietf:params:acme:error:unknownDelegation`.[¶](#section-2.3.1.3-6){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#sec-profile-star-order-journey}
::: {#section-2.3.2 .section}
#### [2.3.2.](#section-2.3.2){.section-number .selfRef} [Order Object Transmitted from NDC to IdO and to ACME Server (STAR)](#name-order-object-transmitted-fr){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-order-object-transmitted-fr}

If the delegation is for a STAR certificate, the request object created
by the NDC:[¶](#section-2.3.2-1){.pilcrow}

-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} have a `delegation` attribute indicating the
    preconfigured delegation that applies to this
    Order;[¶](#section-2.3.2-2.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-2.1}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} have entries in the `identifiers` field for each
    delegated name present in the
    configuration;[¶](#section-2.3.2-2.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-2.2}
-   [[MUST NOT]{.bcp14} contain the `notBefore` and `notAfter` fields;
    and[¶](#section-2.3.2-2.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-2.3}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} contain an `auto-renewal` object and, inside it, the
    fields listed in [Section
    3.1.1](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8739#section-3.1.1){.relref}
    of \[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\]. In particular, the
    `allow-certificate-get` attribute [MUST]{.bcp14} be present and set
    to true.[¶](#section-2.3.2-2.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-2.4}

[]{#name-new-star-order-from-ndc}

::: {#fig-star-ndc-neworder}
::: {#section-2.3.2-3.1}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-json}
POST /acme/new-order HTTP/1.1
Host: acme.ido.example
Content-Type: application/jose+json

{
  "protected": base64url({
    "alg": "ES256",
    "kid": "https://acme.ido.example/acme/acct/evOfKhNU60wg",
    "nonce": "Alc00Ap6Rt7GMkEl3L1JX5",
    "url": "https://acme.ido.example/acme/new-order"
  }),
  "payload": base64url({
    "identifiers": [
      {
        "type": "dns",
        "value": "abc.ido.example"
      }
    ],
    "auto-renewal": {
      "end-date": "2021-04-20T00:00:00Z",
      "lifetime": 345600,          // 4 days
      "allow-certificate-get": true
    },
    "delegation":
      "https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegation/gm0wfLYHBen"
  }),
  "signature": "g454e3hdBlkT4AEw...nKePnUyZTjGtXZ6H"
}
```
:::

[Figure 4](#figure-4){.selfRef}: [New STAR Order from
NDC](#name-new-star-order-from-ndc){.selfRef}
:::

The order object that is created on the
IdO:[¶](#section-2.3.2-4){.pilcrow}

-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} start in the `ready`
    state;[¶](#section-2.3.2-5.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-5.1}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} contain an `authorizations` array with zero
    elements;[¶](#section-2.3.2-5.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-5.2}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} contain the indicated `delegation`
    configuration;[¶](#section-2.3.2-5.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-5.3}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} contain the indicated `auto-renewal` settings;
    and[¶](#section-2.3.2-5.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-5.4}
-   [[MUST NOT]{.bcp14} contain the `notBefore` and `notAfter`
    fields.[¶](#section-2.3.2-5.5){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-5.5}

[]{#name-star-order-resource-created}

::: {#fig-star-ido-order-resource-created}
::: {#section-2.3.2-6.1}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-json}
{
  "status": "ready",
  "expires": "2021-05-01T00:00:00Z",

  "identifiers": [
   {
     "type": "dns",
     "value": "abc.ido.example"
   }
  ],

  "auto-renewal": {
    "end-date": "2021-04-20T00:00:00Z",
    "lifetime": 345600,
    "allow-certificate-get": true
  },

  "delegation":
    "https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegation/gm0wfLYHBen",

  "authorizations": [],

  "finalize": "https://acme.ido.example/acme/order/TO8rfgo/finalize"
}
```
:::

[Figure 5](#figure-5){.selfRef}: [STAR Order Resource Created on
IdO](#name-star-order-resource-created){.selfRef}
:::

The Order is then finalized by the NDC supplying the CSR containing the
delegated identifiers. The IdO checks the provided CSR against the
template contained in the `delegation` object that applies to this
request, as described in [Section 4.1](#sec-csr-template-syntax){.xref}.
If the CSR fails validation for any of the identifiers, the IdO
[MUST]{.bcp14} return an error response with status code 403 (Forbidden)
and an appropriate type, e.g., `rejectedIdentifier` or `badCSR`. The
error response [SHOULD]{.bcp14} contain subproblems ([Section
6.7.1](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8555#section-6.7.1){.relref} of
\[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\]) for each failed identifier. If the CSR
is successfully validated, the order object status moves to `processing`
and the twin ACME protocol instance is initiated on the IdO-CA
side.[¶](#section-2.3.2-7){.pilcrow}

The request object created by the IdO:[¶](#section-2.3.2-8){.pilcrow}

-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} copy the identifiers sent by the
    NDC;[¶](#section-2.3.2-9.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-9.1}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} strip the `delegation` attribute;
    and[¶](#section-2.3.2-9.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-9.2}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} carry a copy of the `auto-renewal` object sent by
    the NDC.[¶](#section-2.3.2-9.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-9.3}

When the identifiers\' authorization has been successfully completed and
the certificate has been issued by the CA, the
IdO:[¶](#section-2.3.2-10){.pilcrow}

-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} move its Order resource status to `valid`
    and[¶](#section-2.3.2-11.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-11.1}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} copy the `star-certificate` field from the STAR
    Order returned by the CA into its Order resource. When dereferenced,
    the `star-certificate` URL includes (via the `Cert-Not-Before` and
    `Cert-Not-After` HTTP header fields) the renewal timers needed by
    the NDC to inform its certificate reload
    logic.[¶](#section-2.3.2-11.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.2-11.2}

[]{#name-star-order-resource-updated}

::: {#fig-star-ido-order-resource-updated}
::: {#section-2.3.2-12.1}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-json}
{
  "status": "valid",
  "expires": "2021-05-01T00:00:00Z",

  "identifiers": [
   {
     "type": "dns",
     "value": "abc.ido.example"
   }
  ],

  "auto-renewal": {
    "end-date": "2021-04-20T00:00:00Z",
    "lifetime": 345600,
    "allow-certificate-get": true
  },

  "delegation":
    "https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegation/gm0wfLYHBen",

  "authorizations": [],

  "finalize": "https://acme.ido.example/acme/order/TO8rfgo/finalize",

  "star-certificate": "https://acme.ca.example/acme/order/yTr23sSDg9"
}
```
:::

[Figure 6](#figure-6){.selfRef}: [STAR Order Resource Updated on
IdO](#name-star-order-resource-updated){.selfRef}
:::

This delegation protocol is predicated on the NDC being able to fetch
certificates periodically using an unauthenticated HTTP GET, since, in
general, the NDC does not possess an account on the CA; as a
consequence, it cannot issue the standard POST-as-GET ACME request.
Therefore, before forwarding the Order request to the CA, the IdO
[SHOULD]{.bcp14} ensure that the selected CA supports unauthenticated
GET by inspecting the relevant settings in the CA\'s directory object,
as per [Section
3.4](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8739#section-3.4){.relref} of
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\]. If the CA does not support
unauthenticated GET of STAR certificates, the IdO [MUST NOT]{.bcp14}
forward the Order request. Instead, it [MUST]{.bcp14} move the Order
status to `invalid` and set the `allow-certificate-get` in the
`auto-renewal` object to `false`. The same occurs in case the Order
request is forwarded and the CA does not reflect the
`allow-certificate-get` setting in its Order resource. The combination
of `invalid` status and denied `allow-certificate-get` in the Order
resource at the IdO provides an unambiguous (asynchronous) signal to the
NDC about the failure reason.[¶](#section-2.3.2-13){.pilcrow}

::: {#sec-cname-installation}
::: {#section-2.3.2.1 .section}
##### [2.3.2.1.](#section-2.3.2.1){.section-number .selfRef} [CNAME Installation](#name-cname-installation){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-cname-installation}

If one of the objects in the `identifiers` list is of type `dns`, the
IdO can add the CNAME records specified in the `delegation` object to
its zone, for example:[¶](#section-2.3.2.1-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-2.3.2.1-2 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft}
       abc.ido.example. CNAME abc.ndc.example.

[¶](#section-2.3.2.1-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#sec-profile-non-star-order-journey}
::: {#section-2.3.3 .section}
#### [2.3.3.](#section-2.3.3){.section-number .selfRef} [Order Object Transmitted from NDC to IdO and to ACME Server (Non-STAR)](#name-order-object-transmitted-fro){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-order-object-transmitted-fro}

If the delegation is for a non-STAR certificate, the request object

-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} have a `delegation` attribute indicating the

    Order;[¶](#section-2.3.3-2.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-2.1}

    true.[¶](#section-2.3.3-2.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-2.3}

The order object that is created on the

    and[¶](#section-2.3.3-5.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-5.3}

    setting.[¶](#section-2.3.3-5.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-5.4}

The Order finalization by the NDC and the subsequent validation of the
CSR by the IdO proceed in the same way as for the STAR case. If the CSR
is successfully validated, the order object status moves to `processing`
and the twin ACME protocol instance is initiated on the IdO-CA
side.[¶](#section-2.3.3-7){.pilcrow}

The request object created by the IdO:[¶](#section-2.3.3-8){.pilcrow}

-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} copy the identifiers sent by the
    NDC;[¶](#section-2.3.3-9.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-9.1}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} strip the `delegation` attribute;
    and[¶](#section-2.3.3-9.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-9.2}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} copy the `allow-certificate-get`
    attribute.[¶](#section-2.3.3-9.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-9.3}

When the identifiers\' authorization has been successfully completed and
the certificate has been issued by the CA, the
IdO:[¶](#section-2.3.3-10){.pilcrow}

-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} move its Order resource status to `valid`
    and[¶](#section-2.3.3-11.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-11.1}
-   [[MUST]{.bcp14} copy the `certificate` field from the Order returned
    by the CA into its Order resource, as well as `notBefore` and
    `notAfter` if these fields
    exist.[¶](#section-2.3.3-11.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.3.3-11.2}

[]{#name-non-star-order-resource-upd}

::: {#fig-non-star-ido-order-resource-updated}
::: {#section-2.3.3-12.1}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-json}
{
  "status": "valid",
  "expires": "2021-05-01T00:00:00Z",

  "identifiers": [
   {
     "type": "dns",
     "value": "abc.ido.example"
   }
  ],

  "delegation":
    "https://acme.ido.example/acme/delegation/gm0wfLYHBen",

  "allow-certificate-get": true,

  "authorizations": [],

  "finalize": "https://acme.ido.example/acme/order/3ZDlhYy/finalize",

  "certificate": "https://acme.ca.example/acme/order/YtR23SsdG9"
}
```
:::

[Figure 9](#figure-9){.selfRef}: [Non-STAR Order Resource Updated on
IdO](#name-non-star-order-resource-upd){.selfRef}
:::

At this point of the protocol flow, the same considerations as in
[Section 2.3.2.1](#sec-cname-installation){.xref}
apply.[¶](#section-2.3.3-13){.pilcrow}

Before forwarding the Order request to the CA, the IdO [SHOULD]{.bcp14}
ensure that the selected CA supports unauthenticated GET by inspecting
the relevant settings in the CA\'s directory object, as per [Section
2.3.5](#sec-nego-allow-cert-get){.xref}. If the CA does not support
unauthenticated GET of certificate resources, the IdO [MUST NOT]{.bcp14}
forward the Order request. Instead, it [MUST]{.bcp14} move the Order
status to `invalid` and set the `allow-certificate-get` attribute to
`false`. The same occurs in case the Order request is forwarded and the
CA does not reflect the `allow-certificate-get` setting in its Order
resource. The combination of `invalid` status and denied
`allow-certificate-get` in the Order resource at the IdO provides an
unambiguous (asynchronous) signal to the NDC about the failure
reason.[¶](#section-2.3.3-14){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#capability-discovery}
::: {#section-2.3.4 .section}
#### [2.3.4.](#section-2.3.4){.section-number .selfRef} [Capability Discovery](#name-capability-discovery){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-capability-discovery}

In order to help a client discover support for this profile, the
directory object of an ACME server (typically, one deployed by the IdO)
contains the following attribute in the `meta`
field:[¶](#section-2.3.4-1){.pilcrow}

[]{.break}

delegation-enabled (optional, boolean):
:   Boolean flag indicating support for the profile specified in this
    memo. An ACME server that supports this delegation profile
    [MUST]{.bcp14} include this key and [MUST]{.bcp14} set it to
    true.[¶](#section-2.3.4-2.2){.pilcrow}
:   

The IdO [MUST]{.bcp14} declare its support for delegation using
`delegation-enabled` regardless of whether it supports delegation of
STAR certificates, non-STAR certificates, or
both.[¶](#section-2.3.4-3){.pilcrow}

In order to help a client discover support for certificate fetching
using unauthenticated HTTP GET, the directory object of an ACME server
(typically, one deployed by the CA) contains the following attribute in
the `meta` field:[¶](#section-2.3.4-4){.pilcrow}

[]{.break}

allow-certificate-get (optional, boolean):
:   See [Section
    2.3.5](#sec-nego-allow-cert-get){.xref}.[¶](#section-2.3.4-5.2){.pilcrow}
:   
:::
:::

::: {#sec-nego-allow-cert-get}
::: {#section-2.3.5 .section}
#### [2.3.5.](#section-2.3.5){.section-number .selfRef} [Negotiating an Unauthenticated GET](#name-negotiating-an-unauthentica){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-negotiating-an-unauthentica}

In order to enable the name delegation of non-STAR certificates, this
document defines a mechanism that allows a server to advertise support
for accessing certificate resources via unauthenticated GET (in addition
to POST-as-GET) and a client to enable this service with per-Order
granularity.[¶](#section-2.3.5-1){.pilcrow}

It is worth pointing out that the protocol elements described in this
section have the same names and semantics as those introduced in
[Section
3.4](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8739#section-3.4){.relref} of
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\] for the STAR use case (except, of course,
they apply to the certificate resource rather than the star-certificate
resource). However, they differ in terms of their position in the
directory meta and order objects; rather than being wrapped in an
`auto-renewal` subobject, they are located at the top
level.[¶](#section-2.3.5-2){.pilcrow}

::: {#capability-metadata}
A server states its availability to grant unauthenticated access to a
client\'s Order certificate by setting the `allow-certificate-get`
attribute to `true` in the `meta` field inside the directory
object:[¶](#section-2.3.5-3){.pilcrow}
:::

[]{.break}

allow-certificate-get (optional, boolean):
:   If this field is present and set to `true`, the server allows GET
    (and HEAD) requests to certificate
    URLs.[¶](#section-2.3.5-4.2){.pilcrow}
:   

A client states its desire to access the issued certificate via
unauthenticated GET by adding an `allow-certificate-get` attribute to
the payload of its newOrder request and setting it to
`true`.[¶](#section-2.3.5-5){.pilcrow}

[]{.break}

allow-certificate-get (optional, boolean):
:   If this field is present and set to `true`, the client requests the
    server to allow unauthenticated GET (and HEAD) to the certificate
    associated with this Order.[¶](#section-2.3.5-6.2){.pilcrow}
:   

If the server accepts the request, it [MUST]{.bcp14} reflect the
attribute setting in the resulting order
object.[¶](#section-2.3.5-7){.pilcrow}

Note that even when the use of unauthenticated GET has been agreed upon,
the server [MUST]{.bcp14} also allow POST-as-GET requests to the
certificate resource.[¶](#section-2.3.5-8){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#terminating-the-delegation}
::: {#section-2.3.6 .section}
#### [2.3.6.](#section-2.3.6){.section-number .selfRef} [Terminating the Delegation](#name-terminating-the-delegation){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-terminating-the-delegation}

Identity delegation is terminated differently depending on whether or
not this is a STAR certificate.[¶](#section-2.3.6-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#by-cancellation-star}
::: {#section-2.3.6.1 .section}
##### [2.3.6.1.](#section-2.3.6.1){.section-number .selfRef} [By Cancellation (STAR)](#name-by-cancellation-star){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-by-cancellation-star}

The IdO can terminate the delegation of a STAR certificate by requesting
its cancellation (see [Section
3.1.2](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8739#section-3.1.2){.relref} of
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\]).[¶](#section-2.3.6.1-1){.pilcrow}

Cancellation of the ACME STAR certificate is a prerogative of the IdO.
The NDC does not own the relevant account key on the CA; therefore, it
can\'t issue a cancellation request for the STAR certificate.
Potentially, since it holds the STAR certificate\'s private key, it
could request the revocation of a single STAR certificate. However, STAR
explicitly disables the revokeCert
interface.[¶](#section-2.3.6.1-2){.pilcrow}

Shortly after the automatic renewal process is stopped by the IdO, the
last issued STAR certificate expires and the delegation
terminates.[¶](#section-2.3.6.1-3){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#by-revocation-non-star}
::: {#section-2.3.6.2 .section}
##### [2.3.6.2.](#section-2.3.6.2){.section-number .selfRef} [By Revocation (Non-STAR)](#name-by-revocation-non-star){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-by-revocation-non-star}

The IdO can terminate the delegation of a non-STAR certificate by
requesting it to be revoked using the `revokeCert` URL exposed by the
CA.[¶](#section-2.3.6.2-1){.pilcrow}

According to [Section
7.6](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8555#section-7.6){.relref} of
\[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\], the revocation endpoint can be used with
either the account key pair or the certificate key pair. In other words,
an NDC that learns the `revokeCert` URL of the CA (which is publicly
available via the CA\'s directory object) would be able to revoke the
certificate using the associated private key. However, given the trust
relationship between the NDC and IdO expected by the delegation trust
model ([Section 7.1](#sec-trust-model){.xref}), as well as the lack of
incentives for the NDC to prematurely terminate the delegation, this
does not represent a significant security
risk.[¶](#section-2.3.6.2-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#proxy-behavior}
::: {#section-2.4 .section}
### [2.4.](#section-2.4){.section-number .selfRef} [Proxy Behavior](#name-proxy-behavior){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-proxy-behavior}

There are cases where the ACME Delegation flow should be proxied, such
as the use case described in [Section 5.1.2](#sec-cdni-dele){.xref}.
This section describes the behavior of such
proxies.[¶](#section-2.4-1){.pilcrow}

An entity implementing the IdO server role \-- an \"ACME Delegation
server\" \-- may behave, on a per-identity case, either as a proxy into
another ACME Delegation server or as an IdO and obtain a certificate
directly. The determining factor is whether it can successfully be
authorized by the next-hop ACME server for the identity associated with
the certificate request.[¶](#section-2.4-2){.pilcrow}

The identities supported by each server and the disposition for each of
them are preconfigured.[¶](#section-2.4-3){.pilcrow}

Following is the proxy\'s behavior for each of the messages exchanged in
the ACME Delegation process:[¶](#section-2.4-4){.pilcrow}

[]{.break}

New-order request:

:   -   [The complete `identifiers` attribute [MUST]{.bcp14} be copied
        as is.[¶](#section-2.4-5.2.1.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.2.1.1}
    -   [Similarly, the `auto-renewal` object [MUST]{.bcp14} be copied
        as is.[¶](#section-2.4-5.2.1.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.2.1.2}

:   

New-order response:

:   -   [The `status`, `expires`, `authorizations`, `identifiers`, and
        `auto-renewal` attributes/objects [MUST]{.bcp14} be copied as
        is.[¶](#section-2.4-5.4.1.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.4.1.1}
    -   [The `finalize` URL is rewritten so that the `finalize` request
        will be made to the
        proxy.[¶](#section-2.4-5.4.1.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.4.1.2}
    -   [Similarly, the `Location` header [MUST]{.bcp14} be rewritten to
        point to an order object on the
        proxy.[¶](#section-2.4-5.4.1.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.4.1.3}
    -   [Any `Link` relations [MUST]{.bcp14} be rewritten to point to
        the
        proxy.[¶](#section-2.4-5.4.1.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.4.1.4}

:   

Get Order response:

:   -   [The `status`, `expires`, `authorizations`, `identifiers`, and
        `auto-renewal` attributes/objects [MUST]{.bcp14} be copied as
        is.[¶](#section-2.4-5.6.1.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.6.1.1}
    -   [Similarly, the `star-certificate` URL (or the `certificate` URL
        in case of non-STAR requests) [MUST]{.bcp14} be copied as
        is.[¶](#section-2.4-5.6.1.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.6.1.2}
    -   [The `finalize` URL is rewritten so that the `finalize` request
        will be made to the
        proxy.[¶](#section-2.4-5.6.1.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.6.1.3}
    -   [The `Location` header [MUST]{.bcp14} be rewritten to point to
        an order object on the
        proxy.[¶](#section-2.4-5.6.1.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.6.1.4}
    -   [Any `Link` relations [MUST]{.bcp14} be rewritten to point to
        the
        proxy.[¶](#section-2.4-5.6.1.5){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.6.1.5}

:   

`finalize` request:

:   -   [The CSR [MUST]{.bcp14} be copied as
        is.[¶](#section-2.4-5.8.1.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.8.1.1}

:   

`finalize` response:

:   -   [The `Location` header, `Link` relations, and the `finalize`
        URLs are rewritten as for Get
        Order.[¶](#section-2.4-5.10.1.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-2.4-5.10.1.1}

:   

We note that all the above messages are authenticated; therefore, each
proxy must be able to authenticate any subordinate
server.[¶](#section-2.4-6){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#sec-ca-behavior}
::: {#section-3 .section}
## [3.](#section-3){.section-number .selfRef} [CA Behavior](#name-ca-behavior){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-ca-behavior}

Although most of this document, and in particular [Section
2](#sec-protocol-flow){.xref}, is focused on the protocol between the
NDC and IdO, the protocol does affect the ACME server running in the CA.
A CA that wishes to support certificate delegation [MUST]{.bcp14} also
support unauthenticated certificate fetching, which it declares using
`allow-certificate-get` ([Section 2.3.5, Paragraph
3](#capability-metadata){.xref}).[¶](#section-3-1){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#sec-csr-template}
::: {#section-4 .section}
## [4.](#section-4){.section-number .selfRef} [CSR Template](#name-csr-template){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-csr-template}

The CSR template is used to express and constrain the shape of the CSR
that the NDC uses to request the certificate. The CSR is used for every
certificate created under the same delegation. Its validation by the IdO
is a critical element in the security of the whole delegation
mechanism.[¶](#section-4-1){.pilcrow}

Instead of defining every possible CSR attribute, this document takes a
minimalist approach by declaring only the minimum attribute set and
deferring the registration of further, more-specific attributes to
future documents.[¶](#section-4-2){.pilcrow}

::: {#sec-csr-template-syntax}
::: {#section-4.1 .section}
### [4.1.](#section-4.1){.section-number .selfRef} [Template Syntax](#name-template-syntax){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-template-syntax}

The template is a JSON document. Each field (with the exception of
`keyTypes`, see below) denotes one of the
following:[¶](#section-4.1-1){.pilcrow}

-   [A mandatory field where the template specifies the literal value of
    that field. This is denoted by a literal string, such as
    `abc.ido.example`.[¶](#section-4.1-2.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-4.1-2.1}
-   [A mandatory field where the content of the field is defined by the
    client. This is denoted by
    `**`.[¶](#section-4.1-2.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-4.1-2.2}
-   [An optional field where the client decides whether the field is
    included in the CSR and, if so, what its value is. This is denoted
    by `*`.[¶](#section-4.1-2.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-4.1-2.3}

The NDC [MUST NOT]{.bcp14} include any fields in the CSR, including any
extensions, unless they are specified in the
template.[¶](#section-4.1-3){.pilcrow}

The structure of the template object is defined by the Concise Data
Definition Language (CDDL) \[[RFC8610](#RFC8610){.xref}\] document in
[Appendix A](#csr-template-schema-cddl){.xref}. An alternative,
nonnormative JSON Schema syntax is given in [Appendix
B](#csr-template-schema){.xref}. While the CSR template must follow the
syntax defined here, neither the IdO nor the NDC are expected to
validate it at runtime.[¶](#section-4.1-4){.pilcrow}

The `subject` field and its subfields are mapped into the `subject`
field of the CSR, as per [Section
4.1.2.6](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5280#section-4.1.2.6){.relref}
of \[[RFC5280](#RFC5280){.xref}\]. Other extension fields of the CSR
template are mapped into the CSR according to the table in [Section
6.5](#csr-template-registry){.xref}.[¶](#section-4.1-5){.pilcrow}

The `subjectAltName` field is currently defined for the following
identifiers: DNS names, email addresses, and URIs. New identifier types
may be added in the future by documents that extend this specification.
Each new identifier type [SHALL]{.bcp14} have an associated identifier
validation challenge that the CA can use to obtain proof of the
requester\'s control over it.[¶](#section-4.1-6){.pilcrow}

The `keyTypes` property is not copied into the CSR. Instead, this
property constrains the `SubjectPublicKeyInfo` field of the CSR, which
[MUST]{.bcp14} have the type/size defined by one of the array members of
the `keyTypes` property.[¶](#section-4.1-7){.pilcrow}

When the IdO receives the CSR, it [MUST]{.bcp14} verify that the CSR is
consistent with the template contained in the `delegation` object
referenced in the Order. The IdO [MAY]{.bcp14} enforce additional
constraints, e.g., by restricting field lengths. In this regard, note
that a `subjectAltName` of type `DNS` can be specified using the
wildcard notation, meaning that the NDC can be required (`**`) or
offered the possibility (`*`) to define the delegated domain name by
itself. If this is the case, the IdO [MUST]{.bcp14} apply
application-specific checks on top of the control rules already provided
by the CSR template to ensure the requested domain name is legitimate
according to its local policy.[¶](#section-4.1-8){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#example}
::: {#section-4.2 .section}
### [4.2.](#section-4.2){.section-number .selfRef} [Example](#name-example){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-example}

The CSR template in [Figure 10](#fig-csr-template){.xref} represents one
possible CSR template governing the delegation exchanges provided in the
rest of this document.[¶](#section-4.2-1){.pilcrow}

[]{#name-example-csr-template}

::: {#fig-csr-template}
::: {#section-4.2-2.1}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-json}
{
  "keyTypes": [
    {
      "PublicKeyType": "rsaEncryption",
      "PublicKeyLength": 2048,
      "SignatureType": "sha256WithRSAEncryption"
    },
    {
      "PublicKeyType": "id-ecPublicKey",
      "namedCurve": "secp256r1",
      "SignatureType": "ecdsa-with-SHA256"
    }
  ],
  "subject": {
    "country": "CA",
    "stateOrProvince": "**",
    "locality": "**"
  },
  "extensions": {
    "subjectAltName": {
      "DNS": [
        "abc.ido.example"
      ]
    },
    "keyUsage": [
      "digitalSignature"
    ],
    "extendedKeyUsage": [
      "serverAuth",
      "clientAuth"
    ]
  }
}
```
:::

[Figure 10](#figure-10){.selfRef}: [Example CSR
Template](#name-example-csr-template){.selfRef}
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#further-use-cases}
::: {#section-5 .section}
## [5.](#section-5){.section-number .selfRef} [Further Use Cases](#name-further-use-cases){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-further-use-cases}

This nonnormative section describes additional use cases implementing
the STAR certificate delegation in nontrivial
ways.[¶](#section-5-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#cdn-interconnection-cdni}
::: {#section-5.1 .section}
### [5.1.](#section-5.1){.section-number .selfRef} [CDN Interconnection (CDNI)](#name-cdn-interconnection-cdni){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-cdn-interconnection-cdni}

\[[HTTPS-DELEGATION](#I-D.ietf-cdni-interfaces-https-delegation){.xref}\]
discusses several solutions addressing different delegation requirements
for the CDN Interconnection (CDNI) environment. This section discusses
two of the stated requirements in the context of the STAR delegation
workflow.[¶](#section-5.1-1){.pilcrow}

This section uses specific CDNI terminology, e.g., Upstream CDN (uCDN)
and Downstream (dCDN), as defined in
\[[RFC7336](#RFC7336){.xref}\].[¶](#section-5.1-2){.pilcrow}

::: {#multiple-parallel-delegates}
::: {#section-5.1.1 .section}
#### [5.1.1.](#section-5.1.1){.section-number .selfRef} [Multiple Parallel Delegates](#name-multiple-parallel-delegates){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-multiple-parallel-delegates}

In some cases, the content owner (IdO) would like to delegate authority
over a website to multiple NDCs (CDNs). This could happen if the IdO has
agreements in place with different regional CDNs for different
geographical regions or if a \"backup\" CDN is used to handle overflow
traffic by temporarily altering some of the CNAME mappings in place. The
STAR delegation flow enables this use case naturally, since each CDN can
authenticate separately to the IdO (via its own separate account)
specifying its CSR, and the IdO is free to allow or deny each
certificate request according to its own
policy.[¶](#section-5.1.1-1){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#sec-cdni-dele}
::: {#section-5.1.2 .section}
#### [5.1.2.](#section-5.1.2){.section-number .selfRef} [Chained Delegation](#name-chained-delegation){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-chained-delegation}

In other cases, a content owner (IdO) delegates some domains to a large
CDN (uCDN), which in turn delegates to a smaller regional CDN (dCDN).
The IdO has a contractual relationship with uCDN, and uCDN has a similar
relationship with dCDN. However, IdO may not even know about
dCDN.[¶](#section-5.1.2-1){.pilcrow}

If needed, the STAR protocol can be chained to support this use case:
uCDN could forward requests from dCDN to IdO and forward responses back
to dCDN. Whether such proxying is allowed is governed by policy and
contracts between the parties.[¶](#section-5.1.2-2){.pilcrow}

A mechanism is necessary at the interface between uCDN and dCDN, by
which the uCDN can advertise:[¶](#section-5.1.2-3){.pilcrow}

-   [the names that the dCDN is allowed to use
    and[¶](#section-5.1.2-4.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2-4.1}
-   [the policy for creating the key material (allowed algorithms,
    minimum key lengths, key usage, etc.) that the dCDN needs to
    satisfy.[¶](#section-5.1.2-4.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2-4.2}

Note that such mechanism is provided by the CSR
template.[¶](#section-5.1.2-5){.pilcrow}

::: {#two-level-delegation-in-cdni}
::: {#section-5.1.2.1 .section}
##### [5.1.2.1.](#section-5.1.2.1){.section-number .selfRef} [Two-Level Delegation in CDNI](#name-two-level-delegation-in-cdn){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-two-level-delegation-in-cdn}

A User Agent (UA), e.g., a browser or set-top box, wants to fetch the
video resource at the following URI: `https://video.cp.example/movie`.
Redirection between the content provider (CP) and upstream and
downstream CDNs is arranged as a CNAME-based aliasing chain, as
illustrated in [Figure
11](#fig-cdni-dns-redirection){.xref}.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-1){.pilcrow}

[]{#name-dns-redirection}

::: {#fig-cdni-dns-redirection}
::: {#section-5.1.2.1-2.1}
::: {#section-5.1.2.1-2.1.1 .artwork .art-svg .alignLeft}
![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,){.diagram}[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-2.1.1){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

[Figure 11](#figure-11){.selfRef}: [DNS
Redirection](#name-dns-redirection){.selfRef}
:::

Unlike HTTP-based redirection, where the original URL is supplanted by
the one found in the `Location` header of the 302 response, DNS
redirection is completely transparent to the User Agent. As a result,
the TLS connection to the dCDN edge is done with a Server Name
Indication (SNI) equal to the `host` in the original URI \-- in the
example, `video.cp.example`. So, in order to successfully complete the
handshake, the landing dCDN node has to be configured with a certificate
whose `subjectAltName` field matches `video.cp.example`, i.e., a content
provider\'s name.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-3){.pilcrow}

[Figure 12](#fig-cdni-flow){.xref} illustrates the cascaded delegation
flow that allows dCDN to obtain a STAR certificate that bears a name
belonging to the content provider with a private key that is only known
to the dCDN.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-4){.pilcrow}

[]{#name-two-level-delegation-in-cdni}

::: {#fig-cdni-flow}
::: {#section-5.1.2.1-5.1}
::: {#section-5.1.2.1-5.1.1 .artwork .art-svg .alignLeft}
![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,){.diagram}[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-5.1.1){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

[Figure 12](#figure-12){.selfRef}: [Two-Level Delegation in
CDNI](#name-two-level-delegation-in-cdni){.selfRef}
:::

uCDN is configured to delegate to dCDN, and CP is configured to delegate
to uCDN, both as defined in [Section
2.3.1](#sec-profile-dele-config){.xref}.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-6){.pilcrow}

1.  [dCDN requests CDNI path metadata to
    uCDN.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.1}
2.  [uCDN replies with, among other CDNI metadata, the STAR delegation
    configuration, which includes the delegated content provider\'s
    name.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.2}
3.  [dCDN creates a key pair and the CSR with the delegated name. It
    then places an order for the delegated name to
    uCDN.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.3}
4.  [uCDN forwards the received order to the content provider
    (CP).[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.4}
5.  [CP creates an order for a STAR certificate and sends it to the CA.
    The order also requests unauthenticated access to the certificate
    resource.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.5){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.5}
6.  [After all authorizations complete successfully, the STAR
    certificate is
    issued.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.6){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.6}
7.  [CP notifies uCDN that the STAR certificate is available at the
    order\'s `star-certificate`
    URL.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.7){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.7}
8.  [uCDN forwards the information to dCDN. At this point, the ACME
    signaling is
    complete.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.8){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.8}
9.  [dCDN requests the STAR certificate using unauthenticated GET from
    the CA.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.9){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.9}
10. [The CA returns the certificate. Now dCDN is fully configured to
    handle HTTPS traffic in lieu of the content
    provider.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-7.10){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.1.2.1-7.10}

Note that 9 and 10 repeat until the delegation expires or is
terminated.[¶](#section-5.1.2.1-8){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#secure-telephone-identity-revisited-stir}
::: {#section-5.2 .section}
### [5.2.](#section-5.2){.section-number .selfRef} [Secure Telephone Identity Revisited (STIR)](#name-secure-telephone-identity-r){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-secure-telephone-identity-r}

As a second use case, we consider the delegation of credentials in the
STIR ecosystem
\[[RFC9060](#RFC9060){.xref}\].[¶](#section-5.2-1){.pilcrow}

This section uses STIR terminology. The term Personal Assertion Token
(PASSporT) is defined in \[[RFC8225](#RFC8225){.xref}\], and
\"TNAuthList\" is defined in
\[[RFC8226](#RFC8226){.xref}\].[¶](#section-5.2-2){.pilcrow}

In the STIR delegated mode, a service provider SP2 \-- the NDC \-- needs
to sign PASSporTs \[[RFC8225](#RFC8225){.xref}\] for telephone numbers
(e.g., TN=+123) belonging to another service provider, SP1 \-- the IdO.
In order to do that, SP2 needs a STIR certificate and a private key that
includes TN=+123 in the TNAuthList \[[RFC8226](#RFC8226){.xref}\]
certificate extension.[¶](#section-5.2-3){.pilcrow}

In detail ([Figure
13](#fig-stir-flow){.xref}):[¶](#section-5.2-4){.pilcrow}

1.  [SP1 and SP2 agree on the configuration of the delegation \-- in
    particular, the CSR template that
    applies.[¶](#section-5.2-5.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.2-5.1}
2.  [SP2 generates a private/public key pair and sends a CSR to SP1,
    requesting creation of a certificate with an SP1 name, an SP2 public
    key, and a TNAuthList extension with the list of TNs that SP1
    delegates to SP2. (Note that the CSR sent by SP2 to SP1 needs to be
    validated against the CSR template agreed upon in step
    1.).[¶](#section-5.2-5.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.2-5.2}
3.  [SP1 sends an order for the CSR to the CA. The order also requests
    unauthenticated access to the certificate
    resource.[¶](#section-5.2-5.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.2-5.3}
4.  [Subsequently, after the required TNAuthList authorizations are
    successfully completed, the CA moves the order to a \"valid\" state;
    at the same time, the star-certificate endpoint is
    populated.[¶](#section-5.2-5.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.2-5.4}
5.  [The contents of the order are forwarded from SP1 to SP2 by means of
    the paired \"delegation\"
    order.[¶](#section-5.2-5.5){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.2-5.5}
6.  [SP2 dereferences the `star-certificate` URL in the order to fetch
    the rolling STAR certificate bearing the delegated
    identifiers.[¶](#section-5.2-5.6){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.2-5.6}
7.  [The STAR certificate is returned to
    SP2.[¶](#section-5.2-5.7){.pilcrow}]{#section-5.2-5.7}

[]{#name-delegation-in-stir}

::: {#fig-stir-flow}
::: {#section-5.2-6.1}
::: {#section-5.2-6.1.1 .artwork .art-svg .alignLeft}
![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,){.diagram}[¶](#section-5.2-6.1.1){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

[Figure 13](#figure-13){.selfRef}: [Delegation in
STIR](#name-delegation-in-stir){.selfRef}
:::

As shown, the STAR delegation profile described in this document applies
straightforwardly; the only extra requirement being the ability to
instruct the NDC about the allowed TNAuthList values. This can be
achieved by a simple extension to the CSR
template.[¶](#section-5.2-7){.pilcrow}
:::

    name,[¶](#section-6.5-3.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-6.5-3.1}

  extendedKeyUsage   See [Appendix A](#csr-template-schema-cddl){.xref}   \[[RFC5280](#RFC5280){.xref}\], [Section 4.2.1.12](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5280#section-4.2.1.12){.relref}
  subjectAltName     See [Appendix A](#csr-template-schema-cddl){.xref}   \[[RFC5280](#RFC5280){.xref}\], [Section 4.2.1.6](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc5280#section-4.2.1.6){.relref} (note that only specific name formats are allowed: URI, DNS name, email address)

::: {#security-considerations}
::: {#section-7 .section}
## [7.](#section-7){.section-number .selfRef} [Security Considerations](#name-security-considerations){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-security-considerations}

::: {#sec-trust-model}
::: {#section-7.1 .section}
### [7.1.](#section-7.1){.section-number .selfRef} [Trust Model](#name-trust-model){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-trust-model}

The ACME trust model needs to be extended to include the trust
relationship between NDC and IdO. Note that once this trust link is
established, it potentially becomes recursive. Therefore, there has to
be a trust relationship between each of the nodes in the delegation
chain; for example, in case of cascading CDNs, this is contractually
defined. Note that when using standard \[[RFC6125](#RFC6125){.xref}\]
identity verification, there are no mechanisms available to the IdO to
restrict the use of the delegated name once the name has been handed
over to the first NDC. It is, therefore, expected that contractual
measures are in place to get some assurance that redelegation is not
being performed.[¶](#section-7.1-1){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#delegation-security-goal}
::: {#section-7.2 .section}
### [7.2.](#section-7.2){.section-number .selfRef} [Delegation Security Goal](#name-delegation-security-goal){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-delegation-security-goal}

Delegation introduces a new security goal: only an NDC that has been
authorized by the IdO, either directly or transitively, can obtain a
certificate with an IdO identity.[¶](#section-7.2-1){.pilcrow}

From a security point of view, the delegation process has five separate
parts:[¶](#section-7.2-2){.pilcrow}

1.  [enabling a specific third party (the intended NDC) to submit
    requests for delegated
    certificates[¶](#section-7.2-3.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-7.2-3.1}
2.  [making sure that any request for a delegated certificate matches
    the intended \"shape\" in terms of delegated identities as well as
    any other certificate metadata, e.g., key length, x.509 extensions,
    etc.[¶](#section-7.2-3.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-7.2-3.2}
3.  [serving the certificate back to the
    NDC[¶](#section-7.2-3.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-7.2-3.3}
4.  [handling revocation of the
    delegation[¶](#section-7.2-3.4){.pilcrow}]{#section-7.2-3.4}
5.  [handling revocation of the certificate
    itself[¶](#section-7.2-3.5){.pilcrow}]{#section-7.2-3.5}

The first part is covered by the NDC\'s ACME account that is
administered by the IdO, whose security relies on the correct handling
of the associated key pair. When a compromise of the private key is
detected, the delegate [MUST]{.bcp14} use the account deactivation
procedures defined in [Section
7.3.6](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8555#section-7.3.6){.relref} of
\[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\].[¶](#section-7.2-4){.pilcrow}

The second part is covered by the act of checking an NDC\'s certificate
request against the intended CSR template. The steps of shaping the CSR
template correctly, selecting the right CSR template to check against
the presented CSR, and making sure that the presented CSR matches the
selected CSR template are all security
relevant.[¶](#section-7.2-5){.pilcrow}

The third part builds on the trust relationship between NDC and IdO that
is responsible for correctly forwarding the certificate URL from the
Order returned by the CA.[¶](#section-7.2-6){.pilcrow}

The fourth part is associated with the ability of the IdO to
unilaterally remove the `delegation` object associated with the revoked
identity, therefore, disabling any further NDC requests for such
identity. Note that, in more extreme circumstances, the IdO might decide
to disable the NDC account, thus entirely blocking any further
interaction.[¶](#section-7.2-7){.pilcrow}

The fifth is covered by two different mechanisms, depending on the
nature of the certificate. For STAR, the IdO shall use the cancellation
interface defined in [Section
2.3](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8739#section-2.3){.relref} of
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\]. For non-STAR, the certificate revocation
interface defined in [Section
7.6](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8555#section-7.6){.relref} of
\[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\]) is used.[¶](#section-7.2-8){.pilcrow}

The ACME account associated with the delegation plays a crucial role in
the overall security of the presented protocol. This, in turn, means
that (in delegation scenarios) the security requirements and
verification associated with an ACME account may be more stringent than
in base ACME deployments, since the out-of-band configuration of
delegations that an account is authorized to use (combined with account
authentication) takes the place of the normal ACME authorization
challenge procedures. Therefore, the IdO [MUST]{.bcp14} ensure that each
account is associated with the exact policies (via their matching
`delegation` objects) that define which domain names can be delegated to
the account and how. The IdO is expected to use out-of-band means to
preregister each NDC to the corresponding
account.[¶](#section-7.2-9){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#new-acme-channels}
::: {#section-7.3 .section}
### [7.3.](#section-7.3){.section-number .selfRef} [New ACME Channels](#name-new-acme-channels){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-new-acme-channels}

Using the model established in [Section
10.1](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8555#section-10.1){.relref} of
\[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\], we can decompose the interactions of the
basic delegation workflow, as shown in [Figure
14](#fig-sec-channels){.xref}.[¶](#section-7.3-1){.pilcrow}

[]{#name-delegation-channels-topolog}

::: {#fig-sec-channels}
::: {#section-7.3-2.1}
::: {#section-7.3-2.1.1 .artwork .art-svg .alignLeft}
![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,){.diagram}[¶](#section-7.3-2.1.1){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

[Figure 14](#figure-14){.selfRef}: [Delegation Channels
Topology](#name-delegation-channels-topolog){.selfRef}
:::

The considerations regarding the security of the ACME Channel and
Validation Channel discussed in \[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\] apply
verbatim to the IdO-CA leg. The same can be said for the ACME Channel on
the NDC-IdO leg. A slightly different set of considerations apply to the
ACME Channel between the NDC and CA, which consists of a subset of the
ACME interface comprising two API endpoints: the unauthenticated
certificate retrieval and, potentially, non-STAR revocation via
certificate private key. No specific security considerations apply to
the former, but the privacy considerations in [Section
6.3](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8739#section-6.3){.relref} of
\[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\] do. With regard to the latter, it should
be noted that there is currently no means for an IdO to disable
authorizing revocation based on certificate private keys. So, in theory,
an NDC could use the revocation API directly with the CA, therefore,
bypassing the IdO. The NDC [SHOULD NOT]{.bcp14} directly use the
revocation interface exposed by the CA unless failing to do so would
compromise the overall security, for example, if the certificate private
key is compromised and the IdO is not currently
reachable.[¶](#section-7.3-3){.pilcrow}

All other security considerations from \[[RFC8555](#RFC8555){.xref}\]
and \[[RFC8739](#RFC8739){.xref}\] apply as is to the delegation
topology.[¶](#section-7.3-4){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#restricting-cdns-to-the-delegation-mechanism}
::: {#section-7.4 .section}
### [7.4.](#section-7.4){.section-number .selfRef} [Restricting CDNs to the Delegation Mechanism](#name-restricting-cdns-to-the-del){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-restricting-cdns-to-the-del}

When a website is delegated to a CDN, the CDN can in principle modify
the website at will, e.g., create and remove pages. This means that a
malicious or breached CDN can pass the ACME (as well as common non-ACME)
HTTPS-based validation challenges and generate a certificate for the
site. This is true regardless of whether or not the CNAME mechanisms
defined in the current document is used.[¶](#section-7.4-1){.pilcrow}

In some cases, this is the desired behavior; the domain holder trusts
the CDN to have full control of the cryptographic credentials for the
site. However, this document assumes a scenario where the domain holder
only wants to delegate restricted control and wishes to retain the
capability to cancel the CDN\'s credentials at a short
notice.[¶](#section-7.4-2){.pilcrow}

The following is a possible mitigation when the IdO wishes to ensure
that a rogue CDN cannot issue unauthorized
certificates:[¶](#section-7.4-3){.pilcrow}

-   [The domain holder makes sure that the CDN cannot modify the DNS
    records for the domain. The domain holder should ensure it is the
    only entity authorized to modify the DNS zone. Typically, it
    establishes a CNAME resource record from a subdomain into a
    CDN-managed
    domain.[¶](#section-7.4-4.1){.pilcrow}]{#section-7.4-4.1}
-   [The domain holder uses a Certification Authority Authorization
    (CAA) record \[[RFC8659](#RFC8659){.xref}\] to restrict certificate
    issuance for the domain to specific CAs that comply with ACME and
    are known to implement
    \[[RFC8657](#RFC8657){.xref}\].[¶](#section-7.4-4.2){.pilcrow}]{#section-7.4-4.2}
-   [The domain holder uses the ACME-specific CAA mechanism
    \[[RFC8657](#RFC8657){.xref}\] to restrict issuance to a specific CA
    account that is controlled by it and [MUST]{.bcp14} require
    \"dns-01\" as the sole validation
    method.[¶](#section-7.4-4.3){.pilcrow}]{#section-7.4-4.3}

We note that the above solution may need to be tweaked depending on the
exact capabilities and authorization flows supported by the selected CA.
In addition, this mitigation may be bypassed if a malicious or
misconfigured CA does not comply with CAA
restrictions.[¶](#section-7.4-5){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#csr-template-schema-cddl}
::: {#appendix-A .section}
## [Appendix A.](#appendix-A){.section-number .selfRef} [CSR Template: CDDL](#name-csr-template-cddl){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-csr-template-cddl}

Following is the normative definition of the CSR template using CDDL
\[[RFC8610](#RFC8610){.xref}\]. The CSR template [MUST]{.bcp14} be a
valid JSON document that is compliant with the syntax defined
here.[¶](#appendix-A-1){.pilcrow}

There are additional constraints not expressed in CDDL that
[MUST]{.bcp14} be validated by the recipient,
including:[¶](#appendix-A-2){.pilcrow}

-   [the value of each `subjectAltName` entry is compatible with its
    type and[¶](#appendix-A-3.1){.pilcrow}]{#appendix-A-3.1}
-   [the parameters in each `keyTypes` entry form an acceptable
    combination.[¶](#appendix-A-3.2){.pilcrow}]{#appendix-A-3.2}

::: {#appendix-A-4}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-cddl}
csr-template-schema = {
  keyTypes: [ + $keyType ]
  ? subject: non-empty<distinguishedName>
  extensions: extensions
}

non-empty<M> = (M) .and ({ + any => any })

mandatory-wildcard = "**"
optional-wildcard = "*"
wildcard = mandatory-wildcard / optional-wildcard

; regtext matches all text strings but "*" and "**"
regtext = text .regexp "([^\*].*)|([\*][^\*].*)|([\*][\*].+)"

regtext-or-wildcard = regtext / wildcard

distinguishedName = {
  ? country: regtext-or-wildcard
  ? stateOrProvince: regtext-or-wildcard
  ? locality: regtext-or-wildcard
  ? organization: regtext-or-wildcard
  ? organizationalUnit: regtext-or-wildcard
  ? emailAddress: regtext-or-wildcard
  ? commonName: regtext-or-wildcard
}

$keyType /= rsaKeyType
$keyType /= ecdsaKeyType

rsaKeyType = {
  PublicKeyType: "rsaEncryption" ; OID: 1.2.840.113549.1.1.1
  PublicKeyLength: rsaKeySize
  SignatureType: $rsaSignatureType
}

rsaKeySize = uint

; RSASSA-PKCS1-v1_5 with SHA-256
$rsaSignatureType /= "sha256WithRSAEncryption"
; RSASSA-PCKS1-v1_5 with SHA-384
$rsaSignatureType /= "sha384WithRSAEncryption"
; RSASSA-PCKS1-v1_5 with SHA-512
$rsaSignatureType /= "sha512WithRSAEncryption"
; RSASSA-PSS with SHA-256, MGF-1 with SHA-256, and a 32 byte salt
$rsaSignatureType /= "sha256WithRSAandMGF1"
; RSASSA-PSS with SHA-384, MGF-1 with SHA-384, and a 48 byte salt
$rsaSignatureType /= "sha384WithRSAandMGF1"
; RSASSA-PSS with SHA-512, MGF-1 with SHA-512, and a 64 byte salt
$rsaSignatureType /= "sha512WithRSAandMGF1"

ecdsaKeyType = {
  PublicKeyType: "id-ecPublicKey" ; OID: 1.2.840.10045.2.1
  namedCurve: $ecdsaCurve
  SignatureType: $ecdsaSignatureType
}

$ecdsaCurve /= "secp256r1" ; OID: 1.2.840.10045.3.1.7
$ecdsaCurve /= "secp384r1" ; OID: 1.3.132.0.34
$ecdsaCurve /= "secp521r1" ; OID: 1.3.132.0.3

$ecdsaSignatureType /= "ecdsa-with-SHA256" ; paired with secp256r1
$ecdsaSignatureType /= "ecdsa-with-SHA384" ; paired with secp384r1
$ecdsaSignatureType /= "ecdsa-with-SHA512" ; paired with secp521r1

subjectaltname = {
  ? DNS: [ + regtext-or-wildcard ]
  ? Email: [ + regtext ]
  ? URI: [ + regtext ]
  * $$subjectaltname-extension
}

extensions = {
  ? keyUsage: [ + keyUsageType ]
  ? extendedKeyUsage: [ + extendedKeyUsageType ]
  subjectAltName: non-empty<subjectaltname>
}

keyUsageType /= "digitalSignature"
keyUsageType /= "nonRepudiation"
keyUsageType /= "keyEncipherment"
keyUsageType /= "dataEncipherment"
keyUsageType /= "keyAgreement"
keyUsageType /= "keyCertSign"
keyUsageType /= "cRLSign"
keyUsageType /= "encipherOnly"
keyUsageType /= "decipherOnly"

extendedKeyUsageType /= "serverAuth"
extendedKeyUsageType /= "clientAuth"
extendedKeyUsageType /= "codeSigning"
extendedKeyUsageType /= "emailProtection"
extendedKeyUsageType /= "timeStamping"
extendedKeyUsageType /= "OCSPSigning"
extendedKeyUsageType /= oid

oid = text .regexp "([0-2])((\.0)|(\.[1-9][0-9]*))*"
```

[¶](#appendix-A-4){.pilcrow}
:::

::: {#appendix-B .section}
## [Appendix B.](#appendix-B){.section-number .selfRef} [CSR Template: JSON Schema](#name-csr-template-json-schema){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-csr-template-json-schema}

This appendix includes an alternative, nonnormative JSON Schema
definition of the CSR template. The syntax used is that of draft 7 of
JSON Schema, which is documented in
\[[json-schema-07](#I-D.handrews-json-schema-validation){.xref}\]. Note
that later versions of this (now-expired) draft describe later versions
of the JSON Schema syntax. At the time of writing, a stable reference
for this syntax is not yet available, and we have chosen to use the
draft version, which is currently best supported by tool
implementations.[¶](#appendix-B-1){.pilcrow}

The same considerations about additional constraints checking discussed
in [Appendix A](#csr-template-schema-cddl){.xref} apply here as
well.[¶](#appendix-B-2){.pilcrow}

::: {#appendix-B-3}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-json}
{
  "title": "JSON Schema for the STAR Delegation CSR template",
  "$schema": "http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#",
  "$id": "http://ietf.org/acme/drafts/star-delegation/csr-template",
  "$defs": {
    "distinguished-name": {
      "$id": "#distinguished-name",
      "type": "object",
      "minProperties": 1,
      "properties": {
        "country": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "stateOrProvince": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "locality": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "organization": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "organizationalUnit": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "emailAddress": {
          "type": "string"
        },
        "commonName": {
          "type": "string"
        }
      },
      "additionalProperties": false
    },
    "rsaKeyType": {
      "$id": "#rsaKeyType",
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "PublicKeyType": {
          "type": "string",
          "const": "rsaEncryption"
        },
        "PublicKeyLength": {
          "type": "integer"
        },
        "SignatureType": {
          "type": "string",
          "enum": [
            "sha256WithRSAEncryption",
            "sha384WithRSAEncryption",
            "sha512WithRSAEncryption",
            "sha256WithRSAandMGF1",
            "sha384WithRSAandMGF1",
            "sha512WithRSAandMGF1"
          ]
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "PublicKeyType",
        "PublicKeyLength",
        "SignatureType"
      ],
      "additionalProperties": false
    },
    "ecdsaKeyType": {
      "$id": "#ecdsaKeyType",
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "PublicKeyType": {
          "type": "string",
          "const": "id-ecPublicKey"
        },
        "namedCurve": {
          "type": "string",
          "enum": [
            "secp256r1",
            "secp384r1",
            "secp521r1"
          ]
        },
        "SignatureType": {
          "type": "string",
          "enum": [
            "ecdsa-with-SHA256",
            "ecdsa-with-SHA384",
            "ecdsa-with-SHA512"
          ]
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "PublicKeyType",
        "namedCurve",
        "SignatureType"
      ],
      "additionalProperties": false
    }
  },
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "keyTypes": {
      "type": "array",
      "minItems": 1,
      "items": {
        "anyOf": [
          {
            "$ref": "#rsaKeyType"
          },
          {
            "$ref": "#ecdsaKeyType"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    "subject": {
      "$ref": "#distinguished-name"
    },
    "extensions": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "keyUsage": {
          "type": "array",
          "minItems": 1,
          "items": {
            "type": "string",
            "enum": [
              "digitalSignature",
              "nonRepudiation",
              "keyEncipherment",
              "dataEncipherment",
              "keyAgreement",
              "keyCertSign",
              "cRLSign",
              "encipherOnly",
              "decipherOnly"
            ]
          }
        },
        "extendedKeyUsage": {
          "type": "array",
          "minItems": 1,
          "items": {
            "anyOf": [
              {
                "type": "string",
                "enum": [
                  "serverAuth",
                  "clientAuth",
                  "codeSigning",
                  "emailProtection",
                  "timeStamping",
                  "OCSPSigning"
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "string",
                "pattern": "^([0-2])((\\.0)|(\\.[1-9][0-9]*))*$",
                "description": "Used for OID values"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        "subjectAltName": {
          "type": "object",
          "minProperties": 1,
          "properties": {
            "DNS": {
              "type": "array",
              "minItems": 1,
              "items": {
                "anyOf": [
                  {
                    "type": "string",
                    "enum": [
                      "*",
                      "**"
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "string",
                    "format": "hostname"
                  }
                ]
              }
            },
            "Email": {
              "type": "array",
              "minItems": 1,
              "items": {
                "type": "string",
                "format": "email"
              }
            },
            "URI": {
              "type": "array",
              "minItems": 1,
              "items": {
                "type": "string",
                "format": "uri"
              }
            }
          },
          "additionalProperties": false
        }
      },
      "required": [
        "subjectAltName"
      ],
      "additionalProperties": false
    }
  },
  "required": [
    "extensions",
    "keyTypes"
  ],
  "additionalProperties": false
}
```

[¶](#appendix-B-3){.pilcrow}
